WHEREAS, Sharon was a key advisor to Tulane's president and played a vital role
aiding President Scott Cowen in reopening the university after Hurricane Katrina's
floodwaters devastated the city and scattered students to other campuses; and
WHEREAS, Sharon was a champion for the rebuilding of the city post-Katrina and
led efforts to secure two hundred seventy-five million dollars in crucial funding for all the
city's public and private universities; she was named a YLC Role Model by the Young
Leadership Council the spring of 2006; and
WHEREAS, during her tenure at Tulane University, Sharon successfully managed
community relations to secure city approval for a new on-campus football stadium, which
helped to energize the football program; her efforts were also instrumental in kickstarting
the New Orleans BioDistrict and creating a strategic plan for the one thousand two
hundred-acre economic development district aimed at growing the biosciences sector; and
WHEREAS, Sharon founded Neutral Ground Strategies in February of 2025, and in
her final days, she continued to serve higher education by helping the University of New
Orleans increase its funding through her work in hospitals; and
WHEREAS, Sharon also served in leadership roles for various boards, including
Market Umbrella, ReNEW Schools, and the Data Center; and
WHEREAS, Sharon was often referred to as one of the few honest brokers left in the
policy world; she was a steadfast advocate of the truth, constantly strived to make the world
a better place, and acted with respect, honesty, and integrity; and
WHEREAS, Sharon had a deep love of New Orleans and its cultural traditions; she
attended Jazz Fest every year that she lived in the city, became a member of the Krewe of
Muses and the Krewe of Dolly, and purchased Saints season tickets in 2006; and
WHEREAS, above all else, Sharon was a connector of people, a generous and loyal
friend, and the consummate host; she was happiest with a crowded table of family and
friends in her home, where she often hosted dinners large and small; her generosity was not
merely hospitality, but a generosity of the spirit; and
WHEREAS, Sharon leaves behind the legacy of her generosity of spirit that is felt
across the country and the world; left to cherish her memory are her husband, Chris Allen,
her parents, Jim and Diane Morgan, her siblings, Mark Courtney, Courtney Gregory and her
